        <li data-comment-id="comment_blogAndPostId/blog/comment/1560-11948-15080" data-comment-wp-id="15080"  parent-id="" class="comment level0 collapsable" data-badges-advoice="">
            <div class="entity_block">
                <a class="avatar" href="http://blogs.forbes.com/people/chrispacia/">
                    <img src="http://graph.facebook.com/100001237258544/picture?type=square" alt="Chris Pacia" />
                </a>



                <a class="user_name" href="http://blogs.forbes.com/people/chrispacia/">
                    Chris Pacia
                </a>


   		<span class="timestamp">7 months ago</span>
    	</div>

    	<div class="comment_content">
    		
<p>There are a number of problems here:</p> 
<p>1) It’s the stretch of the decade to blame the housing bubble on irrationally. That alone cannot cause the price of real assets to become divorced from the fundamentals for years on end. I think bitcoin is a good example. The “bubbles” we have seen in bitcoin thus far have lasted not years, months or even days, but hours before they burst. Irrationally can’t possibly explain multi-years bubbles. There has to be another cause [cough cough zero percent interest rates].</p> 
<p>2) Someone else did win the Nobel Prize this year as well… Eugene Fama. According to the efficient market hypothesis, Bitcoin is not in a bubble. People estimate the expected future value of bitcoin–let’s just say $100,000–and the probability of that happening, say 5%. Today’s price is a reflection of that probability. If it turns out, as the probabilities suggest, that bitcoin fails, the price will drop to zero. But that doesn’t mean bitcoin is irrationally priced. It just means people are willing to pay $1,000 for a 5% chance at $100,000. I really think much of this behavioral finance is barking up the wrong tree. You’ve got the wrong laureate.</p> 
<p>3) An exponential increase in value is not abnormal. It happens all the time–think Facebook, Google, twitter or any startup that makes it big. The difference is the exponential rise in value takes place when the company is privately held. There were times when zuckerberg saw the value of his holdings double every week. But it was only him and the VCs that experienced this rise and the associated volatility. The public typically doesn’t get to buy in to the IPO until after the exponential growth phase is over. Had they been public companies during the exponential growth phase, would this author and laureate Schiller have deemed them to be a bubble based on irrationality? Probably.</p> 
<p>Bitcoin is unique because it gives the public a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity to buy in during the exponential growth phase. Of course that means lots of volatility but it doesn’t automatically imply the price of Bitcoin is based on irrationally.</p>

    	</div>



    	<div class="comment_controls" data-called-out-state="off">
			<div class="right_col">
				<a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/timworstall/2013/12/09/testing-shillers-nobel-prize-against-the-bitcoin-bubble/?commentId=comment_blogAndPostId/blog/comment/1560-11948-15080" class="permalink">Permalink</a>
