        <li data-comment-id="comment_blogAndPostId/blog/comment/1560-11948-15081" data-comment-wp-id="15081"  parent-id="" class="comment level0 collapsable" data-badges-advoice="">
            <div class="entity_block">
                <a class="avatar" href="http://blogs.forbes.com/people/michaeljohansen/">
                    <img src="https://lh6.googleusercontent.com/-c9WbKuyLqjU/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAMs/qv9YkgUkjPE/photo.jpg?sz=50" alt="Michael Johansen" />
                </a>



                <a class="user_name" href="http://blogs.forbes.com/people/michaeljohansen/">
                    Michael Johansen
                </a>


   		<span class="timestamp">7 months ago</span>
    	</div>

    	<div class="comment_content">
    		
<p>Came to point out what others have pointed out before: shorting is indeed possible within the Bitcoin ecosystem, but non-suprisingly, shorting Bitcoin maybe doesn’t satisfy everybody’s standards of what the instrument should look like, considering that Bitcoin *itself* doesn’t fulfil most of those standards (no central issuer. little government oversight so far. etc)</p> 
<p>I have first hand experience with shorting BTC on bitfinex (disclosure: I traded in the past on this platform, but have no further afiliation with them). The way it works on there is that a market exists for platform users to borrow/lend BTC. It is possible to secure even relatively large quantities of BTC, for very competitive rates, and short them (trades are mostly executed on the Slovenian exhchange Bistamp, the 2nd or 3rd biggest exchange).</p> 
<p>You will note I said “competitive rates” above. It seems very few people are actually *willing* to short BTC right now. Shorting does happen, during all the major the flash crashes, outside those events however, most market participants seem to prefer to go long.</p>

    	</div>



