        <li data-comment-id="comment_blogAndPostId/blog/comment/1560-11948-15128" data-comment-wp-id="15128"  parent-id="" class="comment level0 collapsable" data-badges-advoice="">
            <div class="entity_block">
                <a class="avatar" href="http://blogs.forbes.com/people/jonathanlyons/">
                    <img src="http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/6bf7730b5b8b61eab289b972c6be1495?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G" alt="Jonathan Lyons" />
                </a>



                <a class="user_name" href="http://blogs.forbes.com/people/jonathanlyons/">
                    Jonathan Lyons
                </a>


   		<span class="timestamp">7 months ago</span>
    	</div>

    	<div class="comment_content">
    		
<p>Your objection here seems to be that existing platforms for shorting BitCoins pay out in BitCoins. I really don’t see why this means BitCoin is in a bubble, especially since the fix for this is relatively easy. It is almost certain that platforms will be developed that allow shorting in dollars or other foreign currencies. Just like everything else surrounding BitCoin, this infrastructure can and will be developed.</p> 
<p>If there’s some other reason why regulations and policy will not allow this to happen. Otherwise, it’s just a matter of time until shorting provides a reasonable check on out-of-control speculation.</p> 
<p>It seems like a lot of these articles predicting that BitCoin is going to collapse because it’s a bubble are based on a fundamental misunderstanding of how BitCoin works or can work in the future.</p>

    	</div>



